<description>A close examination of arguments for various forms of skepticism, such as: that you lack good evidence for the existence of minds other than your own; that no one knows anything about the external world; that scientific reasoning is fundamentally flawed. Have any philosophers succeeded in rebutting such arguments, or does rationality require us to reconfigure our outlook to accommodate radical skepticism?</description>
